<subSubSection id="00F14C514FB2EFAC9F57840C9A16F99B" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph id="E920BF0E95612B5DFAA8546CECDA9A9B" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="912BA9E00D38AFEF3FD1AFAF9547EB52" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName id="D494500CF3F67F7650DF1728EE614C1E" class="Insecta" family="Brassolidae" genus="Pavonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pavonia sepioides" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepioides">
<emphasis id="D62388BE0C404AD9F6F0CD7E05429D1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Pavonia sepioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
naturally occurs in Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela. It was only recently described (
<bibRefCitation id="C35E1A04528DFF69EFBFBCC2A8F7E931" author="Fryxell, PA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6510181" refString="Fryxell, PA, 1999. . Flora Neotropica 76" volume="76" year="1999">Fryxell 1999</bibRefCitation>
) as a segregate of 
<taxonomicName id="26914A6CF49FAA8EEB1E5D3BF61E7FAC" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepium">
<emphasis id="55DF9050BFFFBB22557415D88229995A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A. St.-Hil., a more southern species with its main distribution in Brazil and neighbouring territories. These two species, as well as 
<taxonomicName id="AFAF8AB0FBB1C6B0CFDD9E76B0D202B4" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. spinifex" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifex">
<emphasis id="B4EEEC8E287BDEFEE3DE39DBB5C25C4C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. spinifex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Cav., belong to 
<taxonomicName id="61B94BB8F3F6A8C4D33D479089951C1C" class="Insecta" family="Brassolidae" genus="Pavonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pavonia subsp. sect." order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="section" section="Urenoideae" species="spinifex" subSpecies="sect.">Pavonia sect. Urenoideae</taxonomicName>
A. St.-Hil. and are not easily distinguished. They are sometimes grown as ornamentals, especially in the subtropics and tropics, although probably not frequently so (none is mentioned, for instance, by 
<bibRefCitation id="7F0F2CAF275F0A65039EF387894F4902" author="Bird, SA" journalOrPublisher="The European garden flora" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6508904" refString="Bird, SA, 2011. . The European garden flora Vol. 4" volume="Vol. 4" year="2011">Bird 2011</bibRefCitation>
, but see 
<bibRefCitation id="F9A54A00D77DE65F008EB0B9E2333082" author="Huxley, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Macmillan, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509172" refString="Huxley, AJ, 1999. The new Royal Horticultural Society dictionary of gardening. Macmillan, London" title="The new Royal Horticultural Society dictionary of gardening" year="1999">Huxley (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. Some are also found as weeds (
<bibRefCitation id="D312D037603C1DDF43C08C7137C56017" author="Holm, LG" journalOrPublisher="John Wiley &amp; Sons, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509138" refString="Holm, LG, Pancho, JV, Herberger, JP, Plucknett, DL, 1979. A geographical atlas of world weeds. John Wiley &amp; Sons, New York" title="A geographical atlas of world weeds" year="1979">Holm et al. 1979</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="0C76A59C83FEAE4CB7B22E75818ED4A0" author="Randall, RP" journalOrPublisher="Department of Agriculture and Food, Western Australia, Perth" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509474" refString="Randall, RP, 2017. A global compendium of weeds. Department of Agriculture and Food, Western Australia, Perth" title="A global compendium of weeds" year="2017">Randall 2017</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="5A19EEEDBF79B38D04C9F0A039FCE0D0" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. spinifex" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifex">
<emphasis id="5A9157B6FF9565C91B99F91094033223" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. spinifex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably most widely grown (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="69A830E577EED18C1AECE1D3015B9478" author="Sanchez de Lorenzo Caceres, JM" journalOrPublisher="Flora ornamental Espanola, Cactaceae-Cucurbitaceae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509544" refString="Sanchez de Lorenzo Caceres, JM, 2000. . Flora ornamental Espanola, Cactaceae-Cucurbitaceae 2" volume="2" year="2000">
<normalizedToken id="710F511D2CDC3BE16C3AFC55EE8E17D4" originalValue="Sánchez">Sanchez</normalizedToken>
de Lorenzo 
<normalizedToken id="41B6DC4408C1804236DBB7661FE83B8B" originalValue="Cáceres">Caceres</normalizedToken>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
). It has large flowers 40-70 mm across and ovate leaves with cordate bases (
<bibRefCitation id="F3D1D27B390F0DE6BF5A4BE13F4B4065" author="Fryxell, PA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6510181" refString="Fryxell, PA, 1999. . Flora Neotropica 76" volume="76" year="1999">Fryxell 1999</bibRefCitation>
), unlike the plants recently found in Tenerife. These have narrowly lanceolate leaves and much smaller flowers. They correspond with the species formerly named 
<taxonomicName id="0931EC66C6E197500C4D92F20894ED7A" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepium">
<emphasis id="0A30595B3503AC915AD151B376D210A8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="17540A6D4E2852932AE7736139565C87" author="Fryxell, PA" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6510181" refString="Fryxell, PA, 1999. . Flora Neotropica 76" volume="76" year="1999">Fryxell (1999)</bibRefCitation>
segregated plants from northern South America as 
<taxonomicName id="5014DEEDF10397D1CED80FAC277A6608" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepioides" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepioides">
<emphasis id="5A331BDC884FF40509276CDD22DC9FFC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. With the exception of the presence of a few hair tufts in the axils of the nerves of the lower leaf surface in 
<taxonomicName id="04003B1C11A48FF90E0921D94EF2D842" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepium">
<emphasis id="2F91C53E4179D82E2EBE0E0E134F3FAD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, these two species largely overlap in all further character states. These hair tufts are not seen in the Tenerife plant material and, for this reason, they are here ascribed to 
<taxonomicName id="41A06005FA489C5241F4178B8BC41670" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepioides" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepioides">
<emphasis id="BCCBE447D811A24B5B2AFE76263B66D7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It probably is not a coincidence that escaped and locally-naturalised plants in tropical East Africa (Uganda) were also attributed to that species (
<bibRefCitation id="E01763D0D5DE4418DBCDE6789811F2B3" author="Verdcourt, B" journalOrPublisher="Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509933" refString="Verdcourt, B, Mwachala, GM, 2009. Flora of Tropical East Africa. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew" title="Flora of Tropical East Africa" year="2009">Verdcourt and Mwachala 2009</bibRefCitation>
). ' 
<taxonomicName id="C3316C1B9792318A9E0039C72BAAABFB" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepium">
<emphasis id="46FC949387B99D6EDE0F669F74F34CE4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
' has reportedly been known as a garden ornamental in Tenerife (
<bibRefCitation id="50C3DF320D768228979285AF9A14FC0E" author="Reyes Betancort, J. A." journalOrPublisher="Revista de la Academia canaria de Ciencias" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="169 - 190" refId="B6755141" refString="Reyes Betancort, J. A., Perez-de-Paz, P. L., 2000. Contribucion al estudio de la florula del Parque Garcia Sanabria (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Tenerife, Islas Canarias). Revista de la Academia canaria de Ciencias 12 (3-4): 169 - 190" title="Contribucion al estudio de la florula del Parque Garcia Sanabria (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Tenerife, Islas Canarias)" volume="12" year="2000">
Reyes Betancort and 
<normalizedToken id="E8D81BEA7C5837EBEB08EDDFC1077D49" originalValue="Pérez-de-Paz">Perez-de-Paz</normalizedToken>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
). From Portugal, ' 
<taxonomicName id="B219784BF62BA0F62368AD6FF0778D32" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. sepium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepium">
<emphasis id="F61096B035387BEB83CA006BA72C734D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. sepium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
' was recently reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="C0891C6B2BB9A067FCC2F0D59E5A3FAE" author="Almeida de, J" journalOrPublisher="Bocconea" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="231 - 237" refId="B6456203" refString="Almeida de, J, Freitas, H, 2012. Exotic flora of continental Portugal - a new assessment. Bocconea 24: 231 - 237" title="Exotic flora of continental Portugal - a new assessment" volume="24" year="2012">Almeida de and Freitas (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. The species escaped from a Botanic Garden in Lisbon and exhibits invasive behaviour (
<bibRefCitation id="8C9D6052ED310CF936F4DEACF0BD0C91" author="Forte, P" journalOrPublisher="Plant Ecology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6508971" refString="Forte, P, Matos, A, Vasconcelos, T, 2011. Gestao das plantas invasoras - planos de prevencao, controle, condicionamento." title="Gestao das plantas invasoras - planos de prevencao, controle, condicionamento" year="2011">Forte et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="707933669330CEF8875A5D663EB878AD" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
The provenance of the plants observed in Tenerife is unknown. They grow relatively near to the Botanic Garden and on the verge of a hotel garden (foot of fence, covered in 
<taxonomicName id="3E3A87997909BE902179376DBCC4845A" authorityName="Miers" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" genus="Pyrostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyrostegia venusta" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="venusta">
<emphasis id="A261877B779618ADB7047A5E2F487724" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Pyrostegia venusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and may have escaped from one of these (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="15A1D980035A3E4E0B8DC9191BCE1278" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F6510159" captionText="Figure 7. Pavonia sepioides, Puerto de la Cruz, December 2019." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494348" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">7</figureCitation>
). On the other hand, the fruits are long-spined and retrorsely barbed and therefore easily attach to clothing and fur. As a result, species of section 
<taxonomicName id="3E9A745EF15B545DD03B0EDDA61DAC31" class="Insecta" family="Brassolidae" genus="Pavonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pavonia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="section" section="Urenoideae">Pavonia Urenoideae</taxonomicName>
have been introduced widely to foreign regions (see also 
<bibRefCitation id="BD0EC22D5A4163B94EE18C296E813E15" author="Fryxell, PA" journalOrPublisher="Flora of North America North of Mexico" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6510209" refString="Fryxell, PA, Hill, SR, 2015. . Flora of North America North of Mexico 6" volume="6" year="2015">Fryxell and Hill 2015</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName id="4199508185BB6D61423835B498A8BEC1" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. spinifex" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifex">
<emphasis id="1938096D8EE8B32A4AECD1E7389E9CDA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. spinifex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
